    "new_concept": {
      "title": "New Concept",
      "active": true,
      "introduction": {
        "title": "Introduction",
        "active": true,
        "content": [
          {
            "ufli_text": "We have been learning about spelling changes that happen when we add suffixes to words. Today we will learn another spelling change.\r-y + -er, -est, -ed: If the word ends in Y, we often change the Y to I before adding the suffixes -ER, -EST, or -ED. (e.g., happy ➔ happier; happy ➔ happiest; copy ➔ copied)\r-y + -s, -es: If the word ends in Y and we want to add the -S/-ES ending, we follow the same pattern and change Y to I then add -ES. (e.g., puppy ➔ puppies; cry ➔ cries)\r-y + -ing: We do not change Y to I when adding -ING. (e.g. say ➔ saying, copy ➔ copying)"
          }
        ]
      },
